     <div class="spacer-small"></div>
    <div class="blog-content content-entryindent ">
        "I'm sorry Sir, but we're out of regular coffee.  Would you care for some decaf?" the flight attendant asked as she reached for the evil pot of low-octane coffee.
<br/>
<br/>"Nevermind.  I think I'll switch to Coke." I said as I took the bright red can from her hands.  How do you run out of coffee on an airplane?  That's like running out of beer during a hockey game.
<br/>
<br/>The flight into San Diego was uneventful, and before I knew it I was in a rental car headed towards MMM headquarters.  The weather was beautiful and traffic wasn't too bad.
<br/>
<br/>After a quick check-in with the receptionist and security at the MMM headquarters building, I was escorted to a small conference room that was quite possibly colder than parts of Antarctica. 
<br/>
<br/>I opened my equipment bag and removed my prized Apple Powerbook.  A quick flip of the screen and it woke from sleep instantly.  Several seconds later I was logged in and busily creating case file notes.
<br/>
<br/>The conference door opened briefly to reveal the head of a very attractive female with a smile that consumed the entire lower portion of her face.
<br/>
<br/>"Chief?  HI!  I'm Lola, Mr. Krump's personal assistant.  Mr. Krump will be with you shortly, he's on an international call that should be wrapping up in a minute or two." 
<br/>
<br/>I couldn't help but smile back, my eyes partially blinded by the recent glow of teeth bleaching. 
<br/>
<br/>"No worries, I have some notes to work on.  Can I bother you for some coffee, please?" I begged.
<br/>
<br/>"SURE!  No problem!" Lola said with the enthusiasm of a seventeen year-old cheerleader.   The door closed and minutes later Lola appeared with a ceramic mug of hot coffee complete with the MMM logo.
<br/>
<br/>"Can I keep this mug?  Very cool!" I joked.
<br/>
<br/>"SURE!  No problem!" Lola said as she exited the conference room.
<br/>
<br/>I was suddenly under the impression that MMM had developed personal assistant robots.  Good grief.
<br/>
<br/>After a few sips of coffee, my brain was awake and processing the information that MMM had sent me via electronic mail.  
<br/>
<br/>Item number one was a timeline of events that lead to MMM discovering that their systems were being breached.  Item number two was a very nice diagram of the gaming network for Huge Kingdom, and it was quite impressive.  Item number three was a one hundred page document describing how Huge Kingdom was designed and implemented.  This particular document had "company confidential" stamped on every page in bright red ink. 
<br/>
<br/>"Well, at least they have information classification nailed down." I laughed to myself.
<br/>
<br/>As I read the design document I jotted down a very brief (and incomplete) risk analysis of the system.  I was barely halfway through the design document when I realized that I had been sitting in the conference room for nearly an hour.  
<br/>
<br/>What was keeping Mr. Krump?
<br/>
<br/>The conference room door opened almost on cue, and in came Ronald Krump with two people  that I hadn't seen before.  You couldn't miss Krump because his picture had been plastered through several trade magazines thanks to the recent success of Huge Kingdom.
<br/>
<br/>"Chief!  Hi, I'm Ronald Krump.  On my left is our chief architect Steven Hu, and on my right is the project manager for Huge Kingdom, Arlie Brown." Krump said as we all shook hands. 
<br/>
<br/>After the usual introductions and jokes about how poor the weather in San Diego was, we got down to business.
<br/>
<br/>We spent the early part of our discussion on the history of Huge Kingdom and what MMM felt their biggest risks were in the online gaming world.  Steven gave an excellent thirty minute overview of the technical architecture of the product, and Arlie filled in the gaps where necessary.  I now knew more about what made an online game tick than I ever wanted to.
<br/>
<br/>"Ronald, you mentioned that the product is being abused by an unknown party or parties, and to the best of your knowledge they are simply manipulating things within the game, correct?" I asked.
<br/>
<br/>Ronald began to speak with his hands in an enthusiastic manner.  "Yes, yes, that's it in a nutshell.  I have asked Steven to lead a small group of MMM employees to help you with your investigation.  If you need anything, just ask." 
<br/>
<br/>"Actually, I do need some help right now." I responded.
<br/>
<br/>"SURE!  What do you need?" Steven asked in an enthusiastic manner that seem to be contagious around the office.
<br/>
<br/>"I need help setting a trap." I said, crossing my arms.
    </div>    
    <div class="spacer"></div>
